All 172 tests pass, typecheck clean. Here's what the experiment shows:

Castling removal alone didn't fix it — with Castling already gone (deleted earlier this session), journey still completed the tang-monk journey around turn 7.3 avg (64% completion rate) and still crushed everyone. So the burst wasn't "free-riding" off Castling specifically.

Deck composition dilution (this change) — I cut tang-monk/je-o-neung/sa-o-jeong/monkey-king from 2 copies each down to 1, backfilled with 7x stone-monkey (was 3x) to stay at 15 cards. Result over two runs (6 and 2 games/matchup):

Completion rate dropped 64% → 50%, and average completion turn pushed back (7.3 → ~9-10).
But win rate barely moved — journey still wins nearly every game once it completes.
Why composition alone can't fully fix this: this ruleset has no draw step — the whole 15-card deck is in hand from turn 1. Card copy count doesn't affect consistency/redundancy the way it would in a normal draw-based game; it only affects how many bodies are on the field to catch the "evolve all allies" effect when tang-monk finishes its walk. Diluting copies delays and slightly softens the burst, but a single tang-monk completion (→ jeon-dan-gong-deok-bul, still 80/80 with a turn-end exile effect) is still enough to win almost every time on its own. The lever that actually controls "how dominant is this" lives in the evolved units' stats/abilities, not in how many copies are in the 15-card list.

I've left the diluted composition in decks.ts since it's a genuine, real (if partial) improvement and matches what you asked for. Let me know if you want to push composition further (e.g. cut je-o-neung/sa-o-jeong to 0 and lean the deck more on monkey-king's own chain) or if this confirms you want to revisit the stat question after all.





